> Did you know the name 'moussaka' derives from the Arabic word for moistened? This
> is likely a nod to the succulent beef, juicy tomato sauce, and softened aubergine
> that make up this delicious comfort dish.

Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Trim the @carrot{1}, then quarter lengthways (no need to peel). Chop widthways
into small pieces.

Trim the @aubergine{1}, then slice into rounds approximately 1cm thick.

Place a large pan over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When hot, add the carrot and fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

Add the @Irish beef mince{250%grams} and @ground cumin{1%sachet}, then cook until
browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling
raw mince. Mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Use a spoon to break up the mince as it cooks. Season with @salt{to taste} and
@pepper{to taste}.

Stir the @passata{1%pack} and @chicken stock{1%sachet} into the pan.

Season with salt and pepper.

Simmer until thickened, ~{15-20%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

Meanwhile, pop the aubergine onto a large (lined) #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with oil, season with salt and pepper then toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer, then roast for ~{15-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Once cooked, remove from the oven.

When the beef mixture has thickened, spoon it into an #oven dish{}.

Lay the roasted aubergine slices on top.

Spread the @creme fraiche{125%grams} over with the back of a #spoon{}, then
sprinkle on the @grated Italian style hard cheese{25%grams}.

Bake the moussaka until it's bubbling and the top has browned, about
~{8-10%minutes}.

Once cooked, remove the moussaka from the oven.

Allow it to stand for a few minutes before serving.

Spoon into #bowls{} to serve.